\section{The fitting function}{

\code{fit_fun(dtm_train, k)} receives the training complement of the fold
(rows of \code{dtm} in the class you passed) and one topic count, and must
return a fitted model OpTop supports: anything
\code{\link[=optop_as_theta_phi]{optop_as_theta_phi()}} adapts \emph{and} \code{\link[=optop_fold_in]{optop_fold_in()}} can project, so
fits from topicmodels, seededlda, NLPstudio, and text2vec via
\code{\link[=optop_warplda]{optop_warplda()}} all qualify. A bare \code{\link[=optop_model]{optop_model()}} does not: it has
no engine to fold unseen documents in. Seeding the engine is
\code{fit_fun}'s own business; make it depend on \code{k} (and, if you want
fold-level reproducibility, on the training row names) for
reproducible fits.
